Year = {{2004}},
Volume = {{38}},
Number = {{3}},
Pages = {{10-18}},
Abstract = {{Ectomycorrhiza of Picea abies and Betula sp. was the subject of the
   research. The ectomycorrhizal morphology and spatial distribution were
   explored at 10 sample plots. The special and spatial analyses of
   macromycetes (especially symbiotrophic ones) were carried out. In the
   sporocarp survey 80 macromycete species belonging to 5 trophic groups
   were observed. Symbiotrophic group dominated. Most abundant in number of
   species were genera Russula, Lactarius, Cortinarius and Amanita.
   Sporocarp inventory revealed that the highest amounts of sporocarps
   belong to such species as Lactarius camphoratus, L. mitissimus and
   Collybia butyracea. According to the data of sporocarp inventories
   Lactarius camphoratus, L. mitissimus and L. necator turned out to be the
   dominant species. During the morphological research 4 types of
   ectomycorrhiza were observed. The most complex forms located in the
   upper layers of soil. The degree of mycorrhization and dry weight of
   mycorrhizal root tips for spruce was significantly higher than the same
   indices for birch. The decrement of mycorrhization from the litter to
   the deeper layers of soil was detected in all observations.}},
