Journal = {{SCIENCE OF THE TOTAL ENVIRONMENT}},
Year = {{1994}},
Volume = {{157}},
Number = {{1-3}},
Pages = {{197-205}},
Month = {{DEC 11}},
Abstract = {{A variety of mushrooms, plants and soils collected in Japanese forests
   were analyzed for Cs-137, Cs-134 and K-40.  The Cs-137 concentrations in
   forest soils ranged from < 0.6-175 Bq/kg on a dry weight basis.  The
   highest Cs-137 concentrations in the soil profiles were observed mostly
   in the surface soil layer (0-5 cm).  Litter layers contained
   significantly less Cs-137 than the surface soil layer.  Concentrations
   of Cs-137 in plants were in general much lower than those in mushrooms. 
   The levels of Cs-137 in 81 mushroom species collected in 1989 and 1990
   varied very widely, ranging from <4 to 16300 Bq/kg (dry wt.), while
   those of K-40 were relatively constant.  The median concentrations of
   Cs-137 and K-40 were 45 and 1110 Bq/kg (dry wt.), respectively.  The
   Cs-137 concentrations in mycorrhizal fungi tended to be higher than
   those in saprophytes, although the concentration range of each type
   varied widely.  High concentrations of Cs-137 in several Hebeloma
   species, ammonia fungi, were observed.  In addition to the
   species-specific accumulation, the concentrations in many mushrooms
   reflected the layers in which their mycelia were growing.}},
